pull_request.title: Adapt Kyber OIDs and avoid testing using downlevel brew releases
pull_request.body:
This eliminates recent CI errors due to 
- latest `liboqs` version (featuring ML-*) not yet being present in "brew'd" distributions
- KEM OID duplication following IETF hackathon OID decision

The approach taken
- checks whether "brew'd" installation contains support for ML-KEM (considered more specific than overly rigid suggestion in #353)
- removes fixed Kyber OIDs and assigns those OIDs to ML-KEM (in absence of a final solution for #351)

pull_request.title: p384_mlkem1024 hybrid added
pull_request.body:
We would like to use a NIST P curve + ML-KEM hybrid and compliance reasons would mandate using P-384 and ML-KEM-1024.
We found that P-384 is the most accepted P-curve. See [CNSA 1.0](https://media.defense.gov/2021/Sep/27/2002862527/-1/-1/0/CNSS%20WORKSHEET.PDF).
From the ML-KEM variants, level 5 will be the most widely accepted. See [CNSA 2.0](https://media.defense.gov/2022/Sep/07/2003071834/-1/-1/0/CSA_CNSA_2.0_ALGORITHMS_.PDF).
Having a P-384 + ML-KEM-1024 hybrid could be useful.
